explanation:
For compliance with the MISRA for-loop well-formedness rule we must inspect any for loops that occur in the target function or in any functions/macros it calls (the rule counts the behaviour of called functions as part of the loop body). The following symbols are therefore required so another analyst can open and review their implementations for any for loops or loop-counter modifications:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: Macro used in the target function; may expand to calls or control structures (including loops) that affect compliance.
- OS_ObjectIdGetById: Direct callee; its body may contain for loops or call further functions with loops.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit: Sub-callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; include to inspect for loops or side-effecting loop counters.
- OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex: Sub-callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; may contain loops or index manipulation relevant to rule 1–4.
- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken: Sub-callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; include to check for loops or loop-counter modifications.
- OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel: Sub-callee of OS_ObjectIdGetById; include for the same reason as above.
- OS_CondVarTimedWait_Impl: Direct callee; likely contains the actual wait/timeout logic and may contain for loops to examine.
- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Sub-callee of OS_CondVarTimedWait_Impl; may perform indexing/loops that affect loop-counter analysis.
- OS_TimeGetTotalSeconds: Sub-callee of OS_CondVarTimedWait_Impl; include to ensure no hidden loops or side effects relevant to loop clauses.
- OS_TimeGetNanosecondsPart: Sub-callee of OS_CondVarTimedWait_Impl; include for the same reason as above.
- OS_printf: Appears via macro/call chain from the target; printing/log utilities sometimes contain internal loops—must be checked if invoked within any loop context.
- OS_ConsoleWrite: Callee of OS_printf; include to inspect for loops inside I/O helpers.
- UT_ExecuteVaHandler: Callee (via OS_printf); unit-test handler that may include loops—include to inspect its code.
- UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType: Direct callee listed in the static graph (test-stub registration); include because the target may call it (via macros) and it may contain loops.
- UT_GetStubEntry: Sub-callee of multiple UT_* stubs; include to check for loops in common stub infrastructure.
- UT_ClearStubEntry: Sub-callee of UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType; include for loop inspection.
- UtAssert_Abort: Sub-callee of several UT_* stubs; include because assertion/abort helpers may contain control-flow/loop code.
- UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData: Direct callee in static graph; include to inspect for loops introduced by context-registration helpers.
- UT_ExecuteBasicHandler: Direct callee in static graph; include since it may dispatch handlers with loops.
- UT_SetHandlerFunction: Sub-callee of UT_ExecuteBasicHandler; include to inspect for loops in handler setup.
- UT_DefaultStubImpl: Sub-callee of UT_ExecuteBasicHandler; include to inspect default stub behavior for loops.
- UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: Direct callee in static graph; include because it may manipulate state or contain loops.
- UtAssert_GetContext: Sub-callee of UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr; include to inspect any loop-containing assert/context helpers.

In short: include the direct callees (OS_ObjectIdGetById, OS_CondVarTimedWait_Impl, OS_CHECK_POINTER/OS_printf) and their transitive callees (object-id helpers, time helpers, console/UT stub helpers) because any for loop in those implementations (or loops inside functions they call) would need to be inspected to determine MISRA compliance for loops in the overall behaviour of OS_CondVarTimedWait.
